post_text: This just in: starting 9/2/2020, breakfast and lunch at school is FREE to our PreK-12 students thanks to a waiver extension granted by USDA through 12/31/20 or until funding runs out. shared_text:
Nancy Bollingberg
May 24 at 8:19 PM ·

Celebrated the Class of 2020 at graduation today. No reception line, so the class paraded down Main Street whole friends and family shouted congratulations and honked to celebrate their day! Just a bittersweet moment.... these kids you've watched grow up for 12 years are off to adult and on to college and starting careers!🎓

I was watching the seniors walk out of FBS one last time with a dear friend and colleague Mr. Warren Strand. He has been by my side everyday for the last 8 years as my Principal, and 23 years working together. As I looked up at him, I also realized this was OUR last graduation.....and we were both moving on to the next chapter of OUR lives! Thank you Mr. Strand for supporting the kids and staff of FBS....but also always believing in my crazy "gut feelings" and believing in my "outside the box" ideas that were always "best for the kids"😉! Best of luck!
.
.
#goodbyeFBS
#bestcareerever
#timetoretire

Guidelines for FBS Graduation
Graduation 2020 will be held on May 24th @ 2:00 PM in the E.S. Killie Gymnasium
Graduation 2020 will be Live on the school Facebook page

Graduation 2020 will take place in the E.S. Killie Gymnasium which has a seating capacity of 600 people. The average number of attendees at graduations for a class of this size (6) has been 150. Therefore, I do not feel we need to limit the number of attendees, but we have developed the following plan to follow recommendations by Governor Burgum, DPI, NDDoH, CDC and the Wells District Health Unit.

Today, Governor Burgum declared that schools will continue with distance learning for the remainder of the year.

Students keep on learning in this new virtual environment, and be sure to give your teachers a big virtual THANK YOU for continuing to deliver you an excellent education!!! THANK YOU to teachers, office staff, administration, cooks, delivery drivers, custodians, and parents for helping to ensure our students continue to be educated. We are COMMITTED to continue providing you a great education.

Stay tuned for news on graduation! We are waiting for some guidance from the Governor and Supt. Baesler on graduation plans. We are, also visiting with our graduates and parents.

We've got this🙌🙌 because we care about each of you!!

Have a great weekend!

Mrs. B

post_text:
I am so proud of this staff! They have jumped in to create learning opportunities for students using "distance" teaching methods....a somewhat unknown world since most have only taught in their classrooms! I have loved observing their spirit for teaching and learning through this challenging time. Their goal....provide kids opportunities to keep on learning!

Students check your email for information from your teachers, and parents watch for an email tomorrow to give some insight what distance learning might look like for your kids. Everyone...please be patient while we all navigate these unchartered waters together ☺️.

Please call with any questions you may have....we will do everything we can to help.

Thank you!
Mrs. B

Good afternoon!

Since Sunday, we have been working with Governor Burgum's office, DPI, and state and local health officials, along with other educational leaders to develop Pandemic Plans for our school districts. The plan we have created will give guidance to everyone to help us continue to educate students. I reviewed the Pandemic Plan with the school board last evening, and would like to share it with you to keep you abreast of the educational planning for your child(ren).

Please know this document is a fluid document which means it could be changing often as we receive updated information or requirements.

The kids are our priority, and we will do whatever we can to continue educating our kids. There will be bumps in the road as we proceed to this new learing environment (i.e. virtual learning), but together we can make it happen! Please see our plan by clicking on the link below.

Mrs. Bollingberg
Mr. Strand

post_text:
UPDATE ON COVID-19 & K-12:
Governor Burgum has issued an Executive Order to close all K-12 schools for 1 week. March 16-20.
The purpose of this closing is to reduce the rate of infection and allow time to plan. (i.e. health care systems, equipment and personnel etc.)

1. This time will help to determine what level we are at.
2. All schools must refine and develop a plan during this week.
3.Mass gatherings and large events are now at 50 people to slow down the spread of the virus.
4. Good hygiene and social distancing is critical in this situation.

Governor Burgum stressed, we need to focus on facts not fear.

Superintendents will be having a conference call at 8:15 tonight.

I will keep you updated as we move through this challenging time.

Nancy Bollingberg

E RECYLING - We are working with American Recycling for the disposal of electronics in our school. They will be at our school next TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 25th. If you have any ELECTRONICS that YOU would like to dispose of, please drop them off at the office by NOON next TUESDAY. They will take anything that "plugs in". NO TV's or large SCREENS or you will be billed for those items. I will let you know when the next pick up date will be, and ask that you do not drop off electronics until I notify you of the next date.

(They are free of charge on most pick up items besides T.Vs, large copy machines, and CRT (big, boxy) monitors. They are also R-2 certified for descruction of data.)

post_text: The first graders are working on measuring. Today they used nonstandard units to measure so many different things! They compared the teacher’s foot to their own, their foot to their partner’s foot, a sheet of paper to a rectangle on the rug, and word wall books to crayons. They found the difference between a crayon, stapler, paint brush, and scissors. They learned it’s easiest if you find a straight line to measure, otherwise your measurement might be crooked and off!

post_text:
Mrs Jones & the 4th Graders Share the True Spirit of Christmas

I wanted to share a fun project that the 4th graders have been working on. We made tie pillows in class and collected some sweet treats that the residents at the Group Home would enjoy. With the advice of Pam Hornbacher, we knew what each resident would like.

We made our deliveries to the Wells County Social Services with gift bags of just pillows. Then we delivered the extra special gifts to the residents at the Group Home. The residents we’re not there yet so she had us place each carefully wrapped package under their tree. Finally we made our way back to the school, it was a memorable fun experience for all.

post_text:
CONCERT INFORMATION
Dear Parents,

This is a reminder that for the Christmas concert we would like to have our students wear “festive” Christmas attire. The attire should not be casual (jeans, t-shirts, sneakers/athletic shoes, etc.), but dressy (girls - slacks, skirt, or dress, blouse or sweater; boys - slacks, button-down shirt or sweater; all - nice shoes. Christmas accessories allowed!)

Our standard black/white is also acceptable, but with some added Christmas accessories, if possible (tie, bows, earrings, etc.). If you need help with attire, please let us know!

On Monday night students should be in their places in the bleachers by 6:20 at the latest. Kindergarten, 1st and 2nd grades will perform at the beginning. At the end of their performance, we will dismiss them to be seated with their parents. Please do not have your child here before 6:15pm (unless they are with you), as they would be unsupervised.

Thanks so much - I’m looking forward to a wonderful evening!

Mr. Reeves

post_text:
Dear Parents,

This year for the Christmas concert we would like to have our students wear “festive” Christmas attire, rather than (or in addition to) our standard black top/white bottom. The attire should not be casual (jeans, t-shirts, sneakers, etc.), but dressy (girls - slacks, skirt, or dress, blouse or sweater; boys - slacks, button-down shirt or sweater; all - nice shoes.
Our standard black/white is also acceptable, but with some added Christmas accessories (tie, bows, earrings, etc.).

If you need help with attire, please let us know!
